column316:
"The aspect that the digital twin of the vehicle can interact with other digital twins (e.g. the infrastructure, other vehicles, ...) and thus lead to an extended simulation of the ""overall system"" of traffic/mobility was briefly mentioned, but in my opinion it is a very important one. As the complexity here increases even further, a simulation of the system is an important "game changer".
Perhaps the realization that less is more, i.e. there is less fundamental diversity in the hardware landscape so that the system remains more deterministic. It's like with mobile devices: So don't limit color or size, limit the number of relevant HW/OS that are in the field.        "

column316: In my opinion, the manipulation of the CPS can be outsourced to other systems. However, this requires the digital twin to regularly exchange data with other systems (e.g. software update management system, security operation center). I missed the aspects of networking/embedding and securing the digital twin a little.

column317:
"I don't think the definition of the digital twin is optimal. In my view, it is not software, but a model that describes reality in real time (as far as possible). From my point of view, it is rather: ""A digital twin consists of models that describe material or immaterial objects from the real world [and provides services to manipulate them]""

Whether you add services to that: That probably doesn't hurt, I think it can be included in the definition. But in my view, a digital twin is not "software". Maybe it's just the wording that's the problem: 

""A digital twin is software that includes models and services..."". The "models" are therefore part of the "digital twin" software, which I don't find ideal. Rather as I suggested above, from my point of view the models are not software.
"
